  "prompt": "Are there international laws against money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several international laws and conventions aimed at combating money laundering. Key examples include:\n\n*   **The United Nations Convention Against Illicit Traffic in Narcotic Drugs and Psychotropic Substances (1988)**: This convention, often referred to as the Vienna Convention, was one of the first major international agreements to address money laundering, specifically related to drug trafficking. It requires signatory countries to criminalize the laundering of drug-related proceeds.\n\n*   **The United Nations Convention against Transnational Organized Crime (2000)**: Also known as the Palermo Convention, this convention extends the scope of money laundering laws beyond drug trafficking to cover a wider range of serious crimes. It requires countries to criminalize the laundering of proceeds derived from transnational organized crime.\n\n*   **The International Convention for the Suppression of the Financing of Terrorism (1999)**: While focused on terrorism financing, this convention also addresses the related issue of money laundering, as terrorist activities often rely on the movement and concealment of funds.\n\n*   **Financial Action Task Force (FATF) Recommendations**: While not a treaty or convention, the FATF is an inter-governmental body that sets international standards and promotes the effective implementation of legal, regulatory, and operational measures for combating money laundering, terrorist financing, and other related threats to the integrity of the international financial system. FATF's 40 Recommendations on Money Laundering are the globally recognized standard. Many countries incorporate these recommendations into their national laws.\n\n*   **Council of Europe Convention on Laundering, Search, Seizure and Confiscation of the Proceeds from Crime (1990) and revised in 2005**: This convention aims to facilitate international cooperation in combating money laundering and the confiscation of proceeds of crime.\n\nThese international agreements and standards provide a framework for countries to enact national laws and regulations to prevent, detect, and prosecute money laundering. They also encourage international cooperation in sharing information, conducting investigations, and extraditing offenders.",
